{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582853"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:57:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:57:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1115"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1115"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.04,0.02,0.9,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70462"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1115"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55926"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"912"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"1243"},{"type":"tags","id":"2259"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14017"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41611"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70462"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a seven-month history of worsening breathlessness associated with a non-productive cough and headache. She has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease diagnosed four years ago. She has a 30 pack-year smoking history and does not take any regular medications. She works as an office administrator.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. Her face is swollen with a suffused pink colour. Her voice is hoarse. Ophthalmological examination reveals right-sided ptosis and a constricted pupil. There is temporal wasting and her BMI is 19 kg/m2. Chest auscultation reveals normal heart sounds with no murmurs and vesicular breathing sounds bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["COPD exacerbation","Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension","Toxic multinodular goitre","Pancoast tumour","Lymphoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of superior vena caval obstruction (facial swelling) and Horner\u0027s syndrome (ptosis, miosis), which are characteristic of a \u003Cstrong\u003EPancoast tumour\u003C/strong\u003E. These tumours arise in the apex of the lung and typically compress surrounding structures including the superior vena cava, brachial plexus, and cervical sympathetic chain. The history of smoking and constitutional symptoms (weight loss) further supports an underlying malignancy, most commonly non-small cell lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECOPD exacerbation\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute worsening of breathlessness, cough, and sputum production. While this patient has COPD, the presence of superior vena caval obstruction and Horner\u0027s syndrome cannot be explained by COPD alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E can cause right heart failure with facial swelling and breathlessness. However, it would not cause Horner\u0027s syndrome, and examination would typically reveal a prominent P2 heart sound and signs of right heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic multinodular goitre\u003C/strong\u003E can cause compression of surrounding structures leading to hoarseness and facial swelling. However, examination would reveal a visible or palpable thyroid mass, and symptoms of thyrotoxicosis would typically be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E can cause superior vena caval obstruction but typically presents with lymphadenopathy, night sweats, and B symptoms. While it remains in the differential diagnosis, the presence of Horner\u0027s syndrome makes a Pancoast tumour more likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Superior vena caval syndrome and Horner\u0027s syndrome are characteristic features of a Pancoast tumour.","Pancoast tumours typically present with shoulder pain, arm pain, and neurological symptoms due to compression of surrounding structures.","Smoking history and constitutional symptoms increase suspicion for underlying malignancy in patients with superior vena caval obstruction."],"references":["Panagopoulos N, Leivaditis V, Koletsis E, Prokakis C, Alexopoulos P, Baltayiannis N, Hatzimichalis A, Tsakiridis K, Zarogoulidis P, Zarogoulidis K, Katsikogiannis N, Kougioumtzi I, Machairiotis N, Tsiouda T, Kesisis G, Siminelakis S, Madesis A, Dougenis D. Pancoast tumors: characteristics and preoperative assessment. J Thorac Dis. 2014 Mar;6 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S108-15. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2072-1439.2013.12.29. PMID: 24672686; PMCID: PMC3966151."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55926"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1115"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18787"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18787"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/af34c9e3-41d8-46c8-811d-71f839c026e3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/af34c9e3-41d8-46c8-811d-71f839c026e3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":459,"height":124}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55926"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T13:36:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T13:12:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1115"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70462"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":